content.problemStatement:
The `continue` statement in a while loop is used to **skip the remaining code** in the current iteration and **move to the next iteration** of the loop. 
It allows you to skip certain steps without breaking out of the loop entirely.

**Syntax:**
```cpp
while (condition) {
    // Loop body
    if (some_condition) {
        continue;  // Skips the remaining code in this iteration
    }
    // Code that will be skipped when the continue statement is executed
}
```
---
**Example:**
```cpp
#include 
using namespace std;

int main() {
    int num = 1;

    while (num <= 10) {
        if (num % 2 == 0) {  // If the number is even
            num++;            // Increment to check the next number
            continue;         // Skip printing even numbers
        }

        cout << num << endl;  // Print the number if it's odd
        num++;                // Increment to check the next number
    }

    return 0;
}
```
**Expected Output:**
```fefault
1
3
5
7
9
```

